Earl "Bubba" Kidder, Jr, 39, is missing. He went fishing with two friends on March 28, 2010 and phoned saying the fishing was going well. However, he never showed up the next morning to attend with his ill mom to a physician appointment. He has not been seen since. His family, children and friends are extremely worried.
His sister says he was picked up by a friend for a weekend fishing trip in the Sherburne Wildlife Management Area.
The car his friend picked him up in, was found extensively burned in Sherburne by Wildlife and Fisheries agents. We're told detectives spent the day questioning the two people who were fishing with Bubba before he vanished.
The missing man's fishing companions state that they have no idea what happened to him. Bubba is 6'2" tall, weighing about 195 pounds with brown hair and eyes. He has a dimpled chin and a large scar on his right arm near his elbow.

circumstances.circumstances:
Adrian Planells, 3425 Florida Avenue, was last seen September 24, 1989, at a lounge with friends. Planells went to the lounge with a coworker from the Casa Garcia restaurant, 8814 Veterans Memorial Boulevard, where he was a dishwasher.
The two left the restaurant about 01.00 and Planells was last seen at Luc Eddie's lounge, 2725 Mississippi Avenue, at about 03.00. Planells decided to stay at the lounge after his friends left at 03.00.

The car Planells was driving the night he disappeared, a blue 1968 Chevrolet Camaro with Louisiana license plate 816B554, has not been found.

Planells, who had never been arrested, lived at home. None of his clothes are missing and a bank account was not touched before or after the disappearance. He had never been away from home without notifying his family.
Foul play is possible.

circumstances.circumstances:
On March 25, 1976, Mary Ann Perez of Chalmette, Louisiana, went out with a girlfriend and left her teen-aged daughter to babysit the younger children.
She told her daughter that she would be calling to check on the children about 10:00-11:00PM. First, Mary Ann called, stating that she was OK and that she would be home shortly. Later, a woman who identified herself as "Dorothy" called, to report that Mary Ann was having car trouble. Mary Ann's family did not know who Dorothy was and was concerned because Mary Ann's car was practically new.

Mary Ann never called and never came home. Her family soon discovered that she had gone to meet her friend at a country-western club on the outskirts of New Orleans.

The next morning, police found Mary Ann's car parked in front of the club, but saw no evidence of car trouble. Three days later, Mary Ann's purse was found in Lake Pontchartrain, ten miles away. It had been weighted down by a brick. But there was no trace of Mary Ann Perez.

(Source info: Charley Project, DoeNetwork, Faces Case #468)
